he lens of Wittgenstein’s moral philosophy, this book pays particular attention to their suggestion of an ethics of war and peace by indirect means, such as prose poetry, spatial form, collage, symbolism, and expressionism. This cultural study reveals new connections between Wittgenstein’s philosophy, his experience during the First World War, and the cultural artifacts produced in its aftermath. By intertwining ethical reflection and textual analysis, Wittgenstein’s Ethics and Modern Warfare aspires to place Wittgenstein’s moral philosophy at the centre of discussions on war, literature, and the arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthics, Moderny20th century. 0aEthics, Modern. 0aEthics. 0aWar (Philosophy). 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xMoral and ethical aspects. 4aArt. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aPhilosophy: Ethics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Individual Philosophers.2bisacsh  aErnst Friedrich Great War.  aEthical silence and cultural representations of war.  aFirst World War and literature.  aJoe Sacco and the Great War.  aLeonhard Frank and the Great War.  aMary Borden and the Great War.  aWittgenstein's ethics and cultural representations of the Great War.  aWittgenstein's ethics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112385340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771123853423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771123853/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles